SYMPTOM_TEXT: The vaccine recipient was already diagnosed with Alzheimer's but was in an early stage of the condition and able to live independently.  Beginning the day after the vaccine there was a marked and sudden cognitive impairment that severely affected ability to live independently, with (subjectively) worse memory, confusion, mood swings and anger outbursts, and loss of ability to do routine household tasks that she was previously able to do consistently without difficulty (e.g. making coffee, writing checks, heating up a frozen meal).   This gradually improved over the next two months.  She has now (as of April 17, 2021) returned to her pre-shot baseline level of function.  Based on this event we have chosen not to subject her to the risk of a second shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Tuesday 3/30 in the evening 3 middle toes on right foot began to swell. Over course of night, toes swelled, turned red, became painful. I iced them overnight and took ibuprofen. By Thursday morning they had developed blisters (the kind you get from hot spots / shoes rubbing). The pain subsided within ~36-48 hours, but the swelling, redness, and blisters remained for several days, slowly resolving over the course of about 7-10 days, with the blisters resolving first and the swelling and redness taking a few days longer. The blisters never did turn purple or peel like chillblains, they just resolved the way normal blisters do.
LAB_DATA: I did not ever consult a physician.

The side effects began the night following my vaccine and lasted the entire next day. It began with fatigue/brain fog, then chills and soreness at the injection site. Once the chills began I was very ill with a fever (100-101), severe aches and pains in my body from head to toe, and experienced  occasional shooting pains. Once the fever went away about 30 hours after my vaccine, I still felt pain and heaviness in my body and had a bad headache. The next day (day 3) was much better- I had no fever but still felt some brain fog, drowsiness, and slight muscle soreness (but no pain).   Two weeks after my vaccine (4/20/21)  I had a very similar experience but am not certain it was related to the vaccine. I developed chills, fatigue, and a headache for the majority of the day. In the evening, it progressed to muscle/joint pain, a severe headache, extreme fatigue, and a 100 degree fever. The next day (today 4/21), the fever has subsided and I feel slightly fatigued. Though I am not sure this was related to the vaccine, it mirrored my initial reaction to the vaccine two weeks prior. It is very unusual for me to get a fever in the 100 degree range and typically only happens every two years or so.
OTHER_MEDS: Occasional use of St. John?s Wort, nettle, and valerian herbs

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 18 hours after my 2nd moderna vaccine, I experienced slurred speech.   When I arrived by car at my destination, I checked into a motel, looked into the mirror and noticed my left side of my face was drooping.   I knew this was sign of stroke.  I called 911 right away.  I was taken to hospital.  They did a CBC the night I arrived and the next day as well.  They did 2 cat scans with and without contrast.  Dr. in the ER determined that I had suffered a Transient Ischemic Attack which was brought on in less than 24hours of the 2nd Modern vaccine shot, and that the TIA was from the vaccine.  THe cat scans did not reveal any blood clots at the time of the scans.  Dr. concluded that they had broken up quickly and that was why  he diagnosed me with TIA.
LAB_DATA: Cat scan with and without contrast, 2 CBCs.

This is a comprehensive neurological evaluation for a very pleasant right handed 32 year old gentleman who denies any past medical history who presents to the hospital with several day progressive visual changes and facial weakness. Patient reports he noted on Saturday that he had somewhat of a headache, he does get headaches from time to time in particular while looking at screens the television, he did have some associated blurring of his vision as well. This was not the worst headache of his life. He had no other associated symptoms. He went to bed on Saturday, he awoke on Sunday and went out to eat and noted that he couldn't form his mouth around the utensil, his face and lips and mouth felt weak. He still did have an intermittent headache and perhaps some neck pain as well at this point. His vision was still blurry. He denies any recent trauma, no car accident no whiplash no falls. He did go to an outside facility where a CT brain was performed and was normal he was told. He has noted yesterday that he could not close his eyes unless he did it manually, also he notes the way his voice sounds is different to him. He has not appreciated any weakness of his arms or legs. He is able to lift up his head off the bed without trouble. He does not think he has a hard time swallowing or breathing per se however he does describe that he is more "aware" of his breathing. He describes paresthesias of his face and around his mouth. No recent URI or diarrheal/GI illness, he did receive the Johnson & Johnson COVID -19 vaccine March 31st. Seen and evaluated in the ED with ed staff. He does report he recently ran a virtual type marathon over the course of 16 days. Clinical context and exam most consistent with that of GBS type variant (?Miller Fisher).  Treated with IVIG.  Symptoms improved after 1 dose.  4 more doses pending.
LAB_DATA: Normal MRI w/wo contrast = unremarkable; lumbar puncture = unremarkable

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt stated after her first Pfizer dose she did not have any adverse reactions that she could remember. Pt. was feeling normal prior to vaccination and stated she had a granola bar and some water for breakfast. Pt was sitting in chair when she alerted technicians about her symptoms. Pt. then stated she began to feel dizzy and lightheaded while sitting in the chair. When asked, pt. said her vision was clear and normal. Pt. has Hx of DM type II, HTN, seasonal allergies and asthma. We assisted pt. to floor in semi fowlers position with a pillow behind her head in position of comfort. I asked pt. if anyone was with her and she stated someone had dropped her off, but was alone currently. Pt. was alert and oriented to person, place and time. I asked if she would like us to call the squad and she responded yes. We called emergency personnel. Pt. was warm to touch, but was complaining of chills. Pulse was 88 bpm, respirations 14. Per pt. she has an allergy to lisinopril and is currently taking several prescription medications, but could not recall any names. Pt. began to notice some wheezing and I asked if she had an inhaler for her asthma. She self-administered 2 puffs of Ventolin which helped with her breathing symptoms. EMS arrived on scene and a brief Hx was given to the squad. EMS took vitals and loaded pt. on cot and transported to Hospital.
OTHER_MEDS: Patient stated she was on several prescription medications but could not remember the names
HISTORY: Asthma, DM Type 2, HTN, Seasonal Allergies

I felt fine from the vaccine, what I am concerned about it how it was administered to myself and the health code violations that took place.   I was vaccinated at station. Upon giving me the vaccination (with one glove on) she got my blood all over my paperwork and her counter where she had other unused vaccines for the following recipients.  with her ungloved hand, took a small alcohol wipe, smeared my blood across her counter top and tried to wipe it off my vaccination record and paperwork. This does NOT kill bloodborne pathogens, and as a nurse she is aware of this.  She did not wash her hand that had my blood on it, and proceeded to try to give me my paperwork with blood on it to hand off to the person checking clients out. I asked for a new one that wasn't contaminated. During this entire thing, someone else who was volunteering or working there watched the encounter and didn't interject or say anything.   When I got up she promptly seated another person to get a vaccine without using a hospital grade disinfectant at her station or even washing her hands.   I am a licensed tattooer iwho takes universal precautions extremely seriously, as I would lose my license if I did not or acted the way she did. I approached an EMT to bring it to someone's attention where he told me they were all volunteers and complaining wouldn't accomplish anything, "it's pointless" I was told. I was absolutely disgusted and appalled at what I saw, especially because of my line of work. So much so, that this reckless behavior is making me hesitant to get a second dose.   I figure nothing will happen as a result of me telling you this, I just need to know that I said something about it, because it's truly disgusting and needs to be brought to someone's attention. Hopefully she is instructed to do better and not put other people's health and safety at risk.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 24 hours after the vaccine I developed a sharp pain on the inside of my left knee, slightly above the knee cap.  There was a soft bump in that area.  At work the next day I felt more sharp pains and bumps developing around my knees on both legs. The backs of my thighs were also beginning to burn.  I contacted the hotline set up at my work for adverse reactions when I got home from work that night.  They were concerned and had me call my doctor. PATIENT ACCOMPANIED BY HIS WIFE REPORTED TO PHARMACY FOR HIS FIRST DOSE OF THE COVID-19 PFIZER VACCINE. THE PATIENT REPORTED THAT HE DID NOT LIKE NEEDLES AND ASKED IF HIS WIFE COULD BE WITH HIM DURING HIS VACCINATION. THE PATIENT WAS VERY ANXIOUS BUT THEN HAD CALMED DOWN. AFTER COMPLETING THE VACCINE , THE PATIENT STATED THAT HE WAS FEELING OKAY PRIOR TO PROCEEDING TO A VACCINE WAITING CHAIR JUST OUTSIDE THE PHARMACY BUT INSIGHT OF THE PHARMACY STAFF. THE WIFE AFTER ABOUT 4 MINUTES POST VACCINATION ASKED IF WE COULD LAY HIM DOWN. ONE OF OUR TECHNICIANS STATED THAT THE PATIENT WAS STARTING TO SEIZE. LAYING THE PATIENT ON THE FLOOR. CONFIRMED THAT 911 SHOULD BE CALLED. OUR TECHNICIANS, COMPLETED THE CALL AND NOTIFIED MANAGEMENT PER POLICY. BY THE TIME THE PATIENT WAS TO THE FLOOR, HIS SEIZING  HAD SUBSIDED (~20-30 SECONDS TOTAL). THE PATIENT WAS ON THE FLOOR AT APPROXIMATELY 09:29 AM ON 4/21/21.STABILIZED THE PATIENTS' NECK AND HEAD WHILE HIS WIFE, A REGISTERED EMERGENCY ROOM NURSE  OBTAINED A PULSE. GRABBED THE CLEAN BLOOD PRESSURE DEVICE SPECIFIC FOR VACCINE EMERGENCIES. A BLOOD PRESSURE WAS OBTAINED 120/63 WITH A HEART RATE OF 57 (NORMAL ADULT CUFF, LEFT ARM, IN THE SUPINE POSITION ).  THE PATIENTS' FEET WERE ELEVATED ON A CHAIR TO RETAIN BLOOD FLOW AND COLOR.  SHORTLY AFTER EMERGENCY MEDICAL SERVICES ARRIVED AND COMPLETED THEIR ASSESSMENT.
LAB_DATA: GRABBED THE CLEAN BLOOD PRESSURE DEVICE SPECIFIC FOR VACCINE EMERGENCIES. A BLOOD PRESSURE WAS OBTAINED 120/63 WITH A HEART RATE OF 57 (NORMAL ADULT CUFF, LEFT ARM, IN THE SUPINE POSITION ).

Continued to feel bad until falling asleep around 3am, woke back up at 6am and took my temperature again and it was still feverish at 99.8 degrees. Woke up once more briefly at 11am but did not take temperature and fell back asleep. Finally woke up for the day at 3pm and fever had broken, temp was back down to normal at 98.5. Still felt a little nauseous but that was probably more from not having eaten all day! Now as of 4/21 I am back to normal. (If it helps for further info, I have also not to my knowledge contracted Covid before, and I had no adverse effects other than a very sore arm from my first shot. SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving the first dose of the Moderna vaccine, I developed a severe headache and COVID arm - a raised red rash on my right arm that was painful, warm, and itchy. After receiving the second dose of the Moderna vaccine, my COVID arm returned, along with body chills and aches, severe back pain akin to back labor, and a severe headache. After about 48 hours, all but the chills subsided and I was left with a pins and needles type feeling in both of my feet. On 04/19/21, I noticed the tingling feeling creep up my legs and into my calves. On 4/20/21, it progressed into my fingertips and my legs felt week. I went into Urgent Care, where they took vitals, my temperature, and did a brief exam. The Nurse Practitioner, called the Hospital's Neurologist, who ordered bloodwork and fit me into his schedule that afternoon. Bloodwork consisted of a full metabolic panel, B12, thyroid, HIV, and Lymes. All results were normal except for the lymphocyte count, which was elevated to 3.6. Following the bloodwork, I met with Dr. who did a neurological exam and ultimtately gave me the diagnosis of Acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (AIDP). Today, 4/21/21, the tingling has progressed into my knees and fingers and my legs feel more weak than yesterday.
LAB_DATA: 4/20/2021: CBC with Auto DIFF - all normal except for lymphocytes #: 3.6 Comprehensive Metabolic Profile: normal Sedimentation rate: normal C-Reactive Protein: normal Vitamin B12: normal TSH: normal Lymes: negative HIV: negative

Call this afternoon regarding safety of in setting of recent Moderna COVID-19 vaccine receipt.     Question related to autoimmune heparin-like thrombotic thrombocytopenia as currently in the news related to J&J vaccine.  Reported incidents that led to FDA pause of J&J vaccine related to arterial events with overt thrombocytopenia and PF4 antibody positive. Limited data available to suggest link to mRNA vaccines at this time but data being collected daily regarding therapies.     Reviewing chart, patient has several risk factors for VTE development (OSA, hx prostate cancer, age, PMR +/- steroids; there is also a mention of unilateral edema in which patient was referred for Doppler but date of this request is unknown to writer so unable to determine if occurred prior to or after vaccine receipt. Also mention of knee pain back to 3/2021 OV with Dr. so unclear if mobility issues although participants in cardiac rehab.     Labs reviewed and mild thrombocytopenia today (148k) and 171k on 10/2020.     Naranjo score 2, suggesting possible correlation but low score overall.     Overall, given presentation and information provided, appears anticoagulation for acute PE is safe. Theoretically would consider enoxaparin 80 mg SQ BID over UFH infusion but defer to medicine.   Additional notes:  2D echo: EF wnl, impaired LV diastolic filling  bilat LE dopplers; negative for DVT  He was transitioned to eliquis RX for PE treatment Discussed AC treatment with on call cardiology, as no stents are in place that I am aware of and the patient denies placement of stents, only CABG in 1995, then stop asa/plavix and continue only with eliquis at this time  Recommend f/u with hematology/oncology in the next 2 weeks for PE management and evaluation  Recommend f/u with Cardiology in the next 2 weeks for further management  AC precautions was reviewed with the patient and his wife prior to discharge and including when to seen medical attention due to increased risk of bleeding events. They both verbalized understanding.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: She was transferred from one ER to another for intraparenchymal bleed and subarachnoid hemorrhage with midline shift. On the week of April 11th she was seen by her periodontist of a bone graft in preparation for a tooth implant. She took minimal ibuprofen and norco after this procedure. However, she also began to feel very nauseated which led to anorexia and worsening malaise. This prompted the pt to present to ER on 4/16 evening, where was given Phenergan, and discharged to home. Symptoms worsened and she re-presented to ED where she was admitted and diagnosed with UTI and colitis. She was started on ciprofloxacin. She denied having had any dysuria or diarrhea. Patient's son says that at 0130 on 4/19 his mother was using both sides of her extremities equally. She had been complaining of headache and leg pain, but by 0130 on 4/19 family did not notice any other obvious changes in patient's movements or behavior. However, at 0730 on 4/19 nurses noticed that patient was unable to move her L arm or leg. She had a CT scan done, which revealed multiple intraparenchymal hemorrhages bilaterally as well as subarachnoid hemorrhage with midline shift. The transferring physician told me that patient had not been on any anticoagulation. Patient and her family deny any history of falls or trauma, denied family history of coagulopathies, and use of blood thinners (including aspirin). No records, labs, or inpatient med list was sent with patient upon transfer. Family says that patient had her first Moderna COVID19 vaccine 3 weeks ago and was due for her second vaccine on 4/23. Labs on admit here are significant for leukocytosis with WBC of 21.9, Hgb of 12.1, platelets of 306, sodium of 140, potassium of 3.1, Bicarb of 22, creatinine of 0.7, glucose of 126, magnesium of 1.8, INR of 1.2. Patient is normotensive, afebrile, and satting well on room air.  Angiogram showed multiple cortical vein thromboses.  Will send hypercoagulable work up, HIT antibody given COVID vaccine 3 weeks ago (Moderna).

I noticed a red bumpy rash forming.  I called my primary physician who advised I take benadryl  That evening, I had a low fever of 99, the chills, felt unwell and fatigued.   When I awoke at 8 am on day 9, I felt very weak, fatigued and like I couldn't hold my head up.  My tongue and upper lip also felt a little swollen.  I had that gut feeling like something was very wrong.  The rash on my arm had gotten bigger and my arm was now swelling.  My primary started my on a medrol dose pack.  Over the next six days,  the raised rash on my arm continued to grow towards my elbow.  It was red, raised, itchy, and very warm and swollen.    My arm did not start fading until Day 14 and was not gone until Day 16.  My primary sent me to the ER on Day 11 to rule out cellulitis which I was advised it was not.  On Day 15-16, Terrible joint pain in my wrists and ankles began and lasted through Day 21.  On Day 18, my arm was still hurting and itchy again.   On Day 17-18, my fingers and hands seemed to be swollen and tips of fingers were red and they hurt terrible to touch anything.  I could not wash dishes or tie shoe laces.  The finger pain was better by Day 20.  Also, I started having ocular dermatitis - swollen eye lids and cystic lesions.  This is continuing today.  Also, I still have deep arm pain although it is not as bad and I have also had right exterior calf pain since Day 2 which has not resolved.

Patient was recently hospitalized for pulmonary embolism with acute cor pulmonale. First noticed increased shortness of breath on 4/4/21 when shoveling mulch and describes feeling "more winded than usual" with physical activity. He presented to the outpatient primary care clinic on 4/6/21 for evaluation and serum labs and TTE were ordered. Labs were notable for a WBC 13.22 and Cr 0.76. TTE showed hyperdynamic LV function with EF >65% and no tricuspid regurgitation with no concern for right heart strain. A follow-up d-dimer was ordered and returned at 1661 resulting in the recommendation to present to the ED.    Upon presentation to the ED, he was hemodynamically stable with an SpO2 of 97% on room air. CT Chest PE protocol was ordered and showed multiple bilateral lobar, segmental, and subsegmental PE with findings suggestive of right heart enlargement was well as areas of pulmonary hemorrhage and developing infarcts. He was given a heparin bolus and he was admitted to the Adult Hospitalist Service.   The following morning, patient's hemoglobin remained stable and he continued to feel clinically well. He was transitioned from the heparin infusion to subcutaneous enoxaparin.  He was discharged on 4/9/21 with a plan for self-injection of enoxaparin and close follow-up with his PCP.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 6 days after shot I got a debilitating headache (the worst headache of my life 10/10 pain).  I went to the ER and they proceeded to do a CT scan and blood work.  Nothing abnormal was found.   The next day I went to Hospital ER due to the head pain, shortness of breath, chest pain and high blood pressure.  They put me on steriods and pain meds and I was referred to a Cardiologist and neurologist.  4 days later I was in the ER again for head pain, my BP was 220/125 due to pain when entering the hospital.  After about 2 weeks, I saw  a neurologist.  He prescribed various pain meds including anti- seizure meds and shots.  The cardiologist feels that it is not a heart issue.   I remain having  daily headaches 6 weeks later but the intensity is lower (5/10).  My BP is now back at a normal level.  I am awaiting 2 more tests.  MRV and spinal puncture test.

Just before 2 PM, I went to pharmacy for my 2nd Moderna shot.  I was due for my 2nd one on the 15th, however I was out of town and rescheduled the 2nd dosage, CT three days later.  The woman who gave me the shot made a noise when she injected me, something like "oh or oops" and suddenly I felt the vaccine run quickly down my arm.  She reached for something to dry it up and said nothing.  I said, was that vaccine running down my arm?  She said yes, but they put more than enough in the syringe so you are fine.  I asked how do you know that?  She didn't respond, told me to wait 15 minutes and that everything would be fine.  The next day, concerned because I have underlying conditions, I called pharmacy back.  The pharmacy manager was unaware of the event and took down my information.  Someone called me back a few minutes later and said they had no direction on what to do next, that they needed to reach out to pharmacy Corporate to report it and the CDC for guidance.  2 days later and I have heard nothing.  I called them back and pharmacy told me that they were waiting on direction, when I asked when I would hear back from them, they had no answer.  I then called the CDC number on the internet and spoke to someone who transferred me to a nurse who read information to me  and gave me directions to fill out an incident report on this website.  Part of what she read me (and then subsequently emailed me) stated that if 1/2 the dosage was given, that is fine, but if less than 1/2 (or if it can not be determined), that an additional vaccine should be given immediately in the opposite arm.  There is no way that the woman who gave me the shot knew how much went in my arm, her verbal reaction and the fact that she rushed me out of there is more than a little concerning.  I now don't know how well I am vaccinated, or what to do next.  Pharmacy told me that there is no data available on the adverse impacts of getting a 3rd vaccine at this point.  WHAT do I do now?

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA  Up until recently, I have had a predictable cycle every 28 days, lasting 7 days, beginning heavy and tapering out.  At the beginning of 2021, I began to enter the perimenopause stage.  My first gap was 37 days (normal period length/strength) and my second gap was 48 days.  My most period came after my first vaccine (at the end of 48 day gap).  I felt it was lighter and less discharge.  It ended after the normal 7 days.  I had 2 days of nothing (as to be expected).  I then began to have some brown discharge and mild cramping/discomfort.  This was not heavy enough for a pad or tampon, only a panty liner was needed.  The brown discharge occurred for about 3-4 days when small amounts of fresh, bright red blood began showing.  This has been occurring for the past 3 days, along with continued mild cramping/discomfort.  I am still in the middle of this discharge which now alternates between fresh blood drops and brown discharge.  I was originally scheduled to have my second dose tomorrow but have decided to postpone it as I don't want to chance blood clots.  Additionally, I am 45 years old and have had 3 children.  I have never had a menstrual cycle closer than 26 days apart.  I have NEVER had any blood discharge after my normal 7 day cycle.  Another matter to consider is that I have a blood clotting disorder called Factor V Leiden, heterozygous.  I did hemorrhage after giving birth to my third child but have had no other clotting issues.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented for second Pfizer covid vaccination today.  She tolerated first vaccination well, however did note some hives on trunk 1 week later, which resolved with zyrtec.  However, did have some residual erythema on chest at presentation today.    I met with her before vaccination and given CDC recommendation to only discontinue vaccination series if evidence of allergic reaction within first 4 hours of vaccination, and patients motivation to complete series, we did proceed with second vaccination.   Approximately 10 minutes after vaccination (11:30 am), she reported feeling hot and tingling in extremities and tongue.  She did not feel short of breath, was able to drink water, but did report mild tightness of throat.   Initial PE:   She had increased erythema on chest, no redness or edema noted of face or tongue. No acute distress/increased work of breathing.  Mild tachycardia, regular rhythm, lungs CTA bilaterally.  Skin warm and dry, conversant and alert.    Vitals initially HR 91, BP 121/85, O2 99%. Temp 97.2 F O2 sats remained 96-100 at all times.  After 5 minutes, pt given 50 mg IM benedryl.  Discussed having husband meet her to drive her home and to be with her this afternoon in case of worsening symptoms.    After 15 minutes, BP 11/5/72, HR70 and O2 100%.  She did begin to feel sleepy, but was able to ambulate to bathroom with assistance without difficulty.    She felt her symptoms had resolved after 30 minutes and felt comfortable returning home with husband.  She will continue benedryl 50 mg q 4-6 hrs for 24 hrs and allegra, which she had added recently for hives.    They have strict instructions to seek medical attention with any change in condition.  I will follow up with her tomorrow as well and then will also report to VAERS.     4/21/21 1:30 pm I spoke with Patient- she is doing very well today.  She states she took an additional dose of benedryl before bed and allegra.  This morning complete resolution, however where she had some hives in the last two weeks have flared and are itchy.  I have asked her to sign up for vsafe and I will submit to VAERS as well.  I also suggested she consider seeing an allergist if she has ongoing issue with hives.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Rash on chest, back, wrist - itchy; Took a dose of benadryl around 10:40AM, no other action taken. Recommendation: Can continue use of OTC anti-histamines (in this case benadryl) if rash continues to itch. Hydrocortisone cream may also be applied to rashes.  These rashes can start a few days to more than a week after the first shot and are sometimes quite large. These rashes are also known as "COVID arm." If you experience "COVID arm" after getting the first shot, you should still get the second shot at the recommended interval if the vaccine you got needs a second shot. Tell your vaccination provider that you experienced a rash or "COVID arm" after the first shot. Your vaccination provider may recommend that you get the second shot in the opposite arm.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the Johnson & Johnson / Janssen COVID-19 vaccine on April 5, 2021. Patient woke up overnight with severe headache that was different than her typical migraines headaches. Headache was "like I never had before", "it's really painful." When I asked if this was the worst headache of her life she responded "probably."  No photophonia, no phonophobia, no nausea, and no vomiting, which she gets every time she has migraines. "This is a different type of headache," she said.  "I usually throw up and my headaches get better." This headache feels like a "balloon in my head." She reported vision changes (blurred vision) 45 minutes prior to our visit which started at 8:19 a.m. on April 21, 2021. ("I was having a problem with peripheral vision, about 45 minutes ago," but not so much now. Patient denies loss of balance (dizziness), seizures, focal weakness, radicular symptoms, saddle anesthesia, sensory changes, slurred speech, numbness, chills, and fever. She was sent to the emergency department for further evaluation. She is a female patient with new, severe headache that is between 18 and 48 years of age, and has received the Ad26.COV2.S (COVID-19) vaccine within 3 weeks of headache onset.
LAB_DATA: Patient was sent to the emergency department for further testing and for an immediate medical evaluation. I do not have access to this records. The patient stated she would be going to the Hospital.

I woke up at 4:00 am after tossing and turning during the night and not having a comfortable deep sleep. I took a few steps in my living room and felt I was about to faint any seconds. Since I live by myself I rushed to my door and laid down outside my apartment door on the floor and put my feet up on the wall to get more blood flow to my brain. The reason I went outside my apartment was because I felt like I could get unconscious and wanted people to find my dead body in case I died. I could not get to my phone in my kitchen to call 911. I laid there for 20 minutes and I was sweating profusely. Then tried to get up after that and I felt I was about to faint again. So I laid down there for another 20 minutes . Then I slowly crawled back to my apartment and slept on the floor for 3 hours. It was around 7:30 when I tried to get up and start the day, but as I got up I was feeling that could faint again. So I went back to sleep again until noon.
HISTORY: I have experienced low blood sugar and sometimes fainting few times during my life.

Patient admitted 4/12/21 with fatigue and abdominal pain.  Found to have UTI but no definite sepsis, and acute renal failure.  Treated with iv antibiotics and iv fluids.  Over next 48 hours developed worsening encephalopathy and thrombocytopenia.  MRI/MRA/MRV showed no acute findings.  Hyperammonemia noted, with no known Hx of cirrhosis; US did not show portal vein or hepatic vein thrombosis.  Encephalopathy worsened, no clear etiology; EEG just showed generalized encephalopathy.  Renal function worsened.  Patient became obtunded and was intubated 4/16/19.  Platelet nadir of 31k.  Dialysis started.  Left common femoral DVT developed.  Patient had DIC type picture.  Respiratory failure worsened, hypotension developed, patient passed away 4/20/21.  No clear etiology of encephalopathy and thrombocytopenia identified, unclear if related to J&J vaccine received 2 weeks prior.

emale client received her first dose of Covid Vaccine (Pfizer, Lot # ER8729, Expiration date: 07/31/2021) at 1132. This minor client, accompanied by her mother proceeded to the observation room for her 15 minute wait period.  Co-lead RN, was present in the observation room assessing another client.  At 1137 this client's mother loudly voiced from the back of the room, "she's feeling dizzy" and co-lead observed client was hanging her head.  Co-lead and EMT1 hurried to her side, and client stated she was feeling lightheaded and dizzy and was suddenly pale and diaphoretic.  EMT1 immediately transferred her from chair to floor with full assistance to prevent a fall/injury.  Client was placed in trendenlenburg position by elevating feet and placing them on the chair.  Client was unresponsive for about 15 seconds until she regained consciousness and returned to baseline mentation.  Client verbalized she "blacked out" and did not remember being placed on the floor.  Client denied pain and respiratory distress. EMT1 called 911 at 1138.  Client and her mother deny she has any medical issues, allergies, medications, or previous incidence of syncope.  At 1145, first set of vitals taken by EMT1 indicate hypotension and bradycardia as follows: BP 68/44, HR 58, and RR 16. At 1145 paramedics arrived and assumed care after receiving report from EMT2.  At 1150 medics took VS with BP 70/50, HR 54, and blood glucose 95, and determined they would start an IV to administer a 500cc bolus for dehydration and to improve BP. Client was also placed on 2L O2 for comfort, no desat noted. At 1200, medics advised client's mother and co-lead they would transport client to the Hospital for further evaluation.  Medics departed at 1205 to transport client to the hospital.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Development of fever blisters (cold sores).   I've had cold sore/fever blister before.  For the past 30 years I would typically get ONE cold sore roughly about every 3-4 years.  Typically it was an indicator I was about to experience an illness.  They were VERY rare and always noted as I will not kiss my children or wife when I would get one.  It would always appear in the exact same location on the upper left part of my top lip.  Very minor cold sore but a cold sore none the less.  My reaction to the 2nd shot was pretty strong.  I had a 102F fever starting at 10PM the evening after the second vaccination.  Very strong muscle contractions and joint inflammation.  The fever and soreness disappeared about 36 hours later and I was fine.  Fast forward a week or two (from the second shot) and I developed an unusual coldsore on my lower lip.  It appeared almost immediately.  I began to apply Abrevia (10% Docosanol) right away.    Honestly it was a very unusual cold sore.  Much larger than any cold sore I had ever had.  It even caused bumps on the  interior part of my lower lip.  This has never happened.    In the past this cold sore would be it.  Then I would be free of them for an extended period.  As of April 21, 2021, I've had 2 additional cold sores.   This is three cold sores in a period of less then 5 weeks.  My diet, exercise and lifestyle have not really changed.  This is VERY odd.

She describes her headache as starting out as temporal and periorbital and then persisting as a frontal discomfort radiating to the back and down the neck.  Associated with this were complaints of blurry vision, photophobia and scotomata.  She denies any focal weakness or numbness/tingling. There was no vomiting or reports of seizures. She denies no recent problems finding words or bouts of confusion.  She denies a history of arrhythmia or palpitations.  Patient received the first dose of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccination on 4/14/2021 into her right arm, 5 days prior to admission (But state records list 4/7/2021 as the date). She did not take any medication to pre-empt side effects such as NSAID, aspirin, H2 blocker, or Tylenol. Initially she developed a sore arm the night of the vaccination. Three days later the headache developed that did not respond to Tylenol PM although it helped her sleep.  She noted taking more than the recommended dose and had mouth dryness.   Patient denies any past history of COVID exposure and any illness c/w COVID where she was not tested.  She has never had her antibody titer checked.   She recently had a dental procedure for an exposed nerve and had a temporary filling placed.  No antibiotics were given and denies having a dental abscess   She described that one of her sisters developed "blood clots from her heart due to atrial fib" after her Pfizer vaccination.  She denies rashes or stigmata of endocarditis, no fevers, chills, or night sweats.   She describes vaginal itching a few days ago and self treated with an anti-yeast cream (Monistat) that relieved symptoms and does not currently have dysuria, frequency or urgency.  On admission, her UA was abnormal and culture is pending but she received one dose of Rocephin and is still without urinary symptoms.   After admission CT scan and MRI of the brain revealed focal areas of likely small subacute embolic infarcts.  (See report)   Since admission she had a reassuring ECHO and no further worsening. Patient received 1 units platelets, IVIG 55gm IV daily x 2 days, Rituximab 560mg IV weekly x 4 (1 dose given during this admission), dexamethasone 40mg IV x 4 days followed by a prednisone taper. Per hematology, "spontaneous development of warm atuimmune hemolytic anemia as well as ITP is of unclear etiology. No malignancy has been isolated. There are some rare case reorts of ITP from COVID vaccination. Ultimately, we cannot prove whether this is due to the COVID vaccine."  Patient was counseled to not undergo the second dose of COVID vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 9 pm I felt fatigue, I went to bed. I took 800 mg of ibuprofen and 1000 mg Tylenol as a pain medication. I drank a bunch of water and took an Emergen-C. I fell asleep by 10:00. I slept and I woke up - shocked awake around 04:30 am - I was super thirsty. My whole body was really sore and stiff and I had a headache.  It was uncomfortable but not unmanageable. I decided to take more Tylenol and Ibuprofen and drink more water again. I got back in bed and was feeling a lot of symptoms - I was really sore in my thigh muscles, lower back, knees and forearms. I had slight chills; I was pretty uncomfortable. I couldn't get back to sleep - I couldn't sleep on my arm with the injection site. This was about 5 pm. I never actually had a fever. But just a lot of fatigue and body aches. For the next day or two - I took 800 mg of ibuprofen and 1000 mg Tylenol every 6 hours. Within 48 hours, the body aches started to subside. I still felt a bit fatigued and I still do feel fatigued to this day. Into the next week, I started feeling like (towards the middle of the week - about the 7th) I was having an urinary urgency feeling. It was a sensation in my lower back like a UTI was coming on. I haven't gotten one in a long time ( I use to). On Friday or Saturday, when I wiped, I was seeing a slight pinkish hue  - a trace of blood - in my urine. Decided to take probiotics and Vit C. and I started to feel better. But Sunday morning, I was back to feeling pretty bad. I visited the Urgent Care on Sunday, the 11th. In the visit, they took a urine specimen. Dr. saw blood in my urine from the test. And an absence of nitrates in the urine and she said it wasn't  a typical UTI. They decided to culture the urine specimen. Macrobid - 2 times a day for 7 days - antibiotics was prescribed. I felt a little better the second day of taking it, I thought, but it was up and down. Culture showed there was no UTI.  Friday, the 16th, I had my annual visit with my PCP, I was feeling okay by this time. But I still had a sensation in my lower back - not a pain but a sensation and I still feel this sensation now (on my left side). She asked me to come back after the antibiotics to take another urine sample. Lab test. I feel some fatigue but I'm doing normal daily life.
LAB_DATA: 11th - Urgent Care - Urine specimen and culture - presence of blood and absence of nitrate; culture - didn't show UTI  Lab test - for antibodies - for COVID- came back negative (don't know which test they ran)
HISTORY: thyroid removed in 2004 (for thyroid cancer) - not affecting me anymore
ALLERGIES: penicillin - sensitivity; seasonal allergies; cat allergies

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About the time I got the 1st vaccine, my chronic diarrhea (usually controlled by 0-1 loperamide 2mg qd) became severe.  Gaseous, explosive diarrhea, 10-15 times/day.  Even taking the loperamide with simethicone, up to 4 times/day, would not stop it.  This went on and on.  On 4-2-21 I took stool samples to lab, ordered by my healthcare provider. Those tests came back (or, I found out the results) on 4-14-21, 3 days after receiving the 2nd vaccine.  They showed that I have Pancreatic Insufficiency.   Fecal Pancreatic Elastase was 132 (norm >200, moderate pancreatic insufficiency 100-200 and severe is <100, per lab report).   Occult blood, lactoferrin, and culture were all negative (stool).  I have to wonder about this "coincidence".   36,000 units tid.  I started these mid-day on 4-18-21 (pharmacy didn't have enough immediately and RX picked up and started when filled on 4-18-21).
LAB_DATA: See above.  Lab delivered stool sample on 4-2-21.  "Reported On" date, per written report, was 4-8-21 at 13:08:00 hours.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Minutes after my injection I walked to sit in observation area (I almost drove home and skipped observation).  I felt flushed and noticed my heart start to race.  I thought that walking around may help, but it didn't.  I asked the nurse to take my vitals and my pulse was 115 and didn't come down.  My BP was also pretty high.  I went and laid down in the ER and was released without any intervention an hour or so later.  A week later my vitals were still abnormally high and I went back to the ER and was treated with some fluids (my endocronologist prescribed beta blockers, but at this point they did not help).  It has been three weeks now and I am still dealing with high heart rate, and am now having to take beta blockers to regulate my pulse.  I was dealing with some on and off low grade fevers which have subsided. I am not able to sleep and have also noticed some numbness in my right foot.  I did not have any of this before 3/29.
LAB_DATA: HCG - negative Vitamin C - 67 Thyroglobin panel - 9.8 (elevated antibodies, but normal TSH) Cortisol - 14 D-Dimer- 270 CBC - normal ECG - normal Echo - normal 48 hour monitor - awaiting results

Patient left for home with father after being observed for 40 minutes

Patient came in for 1st Moderna Covid vaccine. Patient filled out vaccine questionnaire form. Patient stated she has had no allergic reaction to another vaccine or injectable medication. Patient did state that she has allergic reactions to Wheat, corn, eggs, and nuts and does carry an epi pen. Patient stated she was nervous and did have anxiety problems. When going over paperwork with patient  nurse again asked patient is there were ANY medication allergies to which patient replied ?no?. Patient was instructed to wait for 30 minutes in her car after vaccine administration to be observed for any adverse reactions and to honk car horn should she need assistance. Patient agreed and vaccine was administered at 1305. Very shortly after, patient honked horn of car. Nurses went to car with wheelchair. Patient stated her lips were tingling and she felt like she was having anxiety. Patient assisted into WC. While patient was being wheeled back to east entrance, vaccine clinic staging area, patient stated that she was feeling nauseated and felt like vomiting. Patient then threw her head back, eyes closed and patient started to slide from the WC. Nurse assisted patient to the ground. Patient then started to seize and became unresponsive. 911 called at 1309, patient became responsive. First set of vitals taken at 1310. Privacy screen placed, tent canopy was moved over patient and team, linen placed on ground under patient to try and protect her from the hot pavement. Cooling measures taken. Second set of vitals taken at 1316. Patient verbal, alert, responsive, answering questions. Patient drank a small amount of water. Ambulance and fire arrived at 1320. Patient called mother on phone. Nurse secured patients car. Left in ambulance at 1338.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my vaccine around 11 am on 04/14/2021.  Before I left the I did notice my left arm was starting to get sore.  By the time I got home around 3:30pm the soreness had gotten worse and had moved up my arm and across my shoulder and up neck and across the middle of my back on the left side of my body.  I took 2 tylenol extra strength tablets and went to bed around 9 pm.  I was awakened in the middle of the night to very itchy skin across my shoulders, back and neck on both sides front and back.  That last until I went back to sleep about 15 mins later.  I really don?t know.  I woke up on the 15th with only sight soreness in my left arm at the injection site however, later that night while asleep I was awakened again to itchy skin in the same area as the previous night and with the itchiness traveling down my left arm almost to my wrist.  This time I also experience hives and redness on my arm.  Maybe I had redness and hives the night before I don?t know because I didn?t get out of my bed to check.  When I awoke on the 16th, I still had the redness on my arm, but the hives had gone away. The soreness at the injection site was barely noticeable.  On 04/21/2021 I awoke to the same soreness up my arm, shoulder and neck with the addition of soreness going down my arm to just past my elbow.   The level of discomfort being the same as the first day I received the injection on the14th.  It hurts and makes me very cranky

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 4/19 he received the first dose of Pfizer vaccine oh 4 PM.  Administration of vaccine was uneventful.  The next day he noticed sore shoulder at 3 PM on 4/20 he noted he had upper wrist pain that progressed to his right thumb as well as redness with a shiny quality that was consistent with previous gout flares so he took 2 doses of colchicine and 2 doses of Advil which did not relieve his symptoms.  A couple hours later he noted hand numbness and tingling as well as feet numbness and tingling bilaterally.  The numbness progressed to his extremities with the left arm more affected than the right arm (he received vaccine in his left arm).  He had accompanied pain of his extremities and wrists that was described as 10 out of 10.  He then felt 2 episodes of chest tightness and difficulty breathing prompting him to present to the strong ED.  In the ED his exam was notable for hypertension (240/90), tachycardia, wrist flexion in distress and yelling in pain.  His exam also showed bilateral hyperflexion of bilateral wrist with mild swelling and diminished sensation and motor function throughout.  He was administered IV hydromorphone, and Benadryl with dramatic improvement in his symptoms.  His labs are notable for abnormal electrolytes including magnesium, potassium, phosphorus, calcium and he was repleted with magnesium potassium and phosphorus.  He is admitted to ED OBS. overall felt his symptoms were most likely due to gout flare and hyperventilation, not likely related to vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My first dose of the vaccine was administered on March 11th 2021 at Walgreens Pharmacy, Pfizer Lot number EN6199. The side effects from this dose were mild nausea, shakes, chills, dizzy, somewhat disoriented and "foggy" brain. These disappeared the next day. My second dose was on April 1st. at the same facility. This time I had no reaction. On the morning on April 11th I woke up feeling miserable. The symptoms were identical to the side effects of the first dose, except worse. This time I also had a low grade fever. These symptoms dissipated in 36 hours. On April 13th I woke up to the same symptoms again, though milder, lasting about 8 hours. Today, April 21st,, I woke up with the symptoms one more time, lasting about 5 hours. As I am writing this I feel fine again. As a lay person I have no idea if these are all related. The whole scenario  seems rather odd to me. For your information, I had my yearly physical in late March 2021, all tests were normal.
OTHER_MEDS: Calcium                                   Pramipexole            Lumigan Vitamin C                                Lamotrigine            Brimonidine CBD Topical Cream           Atorvastatin            Dorzolamide Quetiapine Fumarate       P

Patient registered in vaccine system under two differently spelled first names with same birth day and last name. He arrived for his "second" dose appointment under the incorrectly spelled name with his vaccination card from his first dose. Patients enter incorrect spelling frequently online when they register so spelling was just corrected and card was filled out. A vaccine clinic was being held in the middle of the store and when the card was filled out the date of the first dose was not noticed by myself. The nurse then administered the vaccine. When the papers were being entered in to the computer it was noticed the patient had just received his first dose one week prior. The patient made no mention was his last dose being so close together.  As soon as it was noticed corporate and Pfizer were both called. Pfizer claims this early dose will count as his second dose and he will not need a third dose. The patient did not express any adverse events during his observation period. Patient was called and told of the incident and expressed no new symptoms since dose. Patient was told to monitor for symptoms of adverse reaction.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: (date of birth: 08/23/1988) received the 1st COVID vaccine (Pfizer, Lot #: EW0171, expiration date: 08/2021) at 12:37 PM. Patient was sitting in the observation area when he flagged medical. At 12:44 PM, Medic  made contact with the patient who stated he felt ?lightheaded.? Patient was conscious, alert, and oriented to person, time, place, and event (COAx4) and appeared to be in mild distress. Respirations were at a rate of 18 breaths per minute and skin was palm, warm, and dry. Pupils were dilated to about 4 mm and were equal and reactive to light. Nurse  then attended to Medic with patient. Patient denied any other complaints or any pertinent medical history and claimed last oral intake was at 10:30 AM, with minimal fluid intake. Patient stated symptoms began about 5 minutes status post vaccine. Patient denied headache, nausea, blurry vision, chest pain, or shortness of breath. Medic instructed the patient to stay in the observation area for an additional 15 minutes and gave the patient a water bottle to drink. At 1:05 PM, patient stated he was ?feeling 100% better.? Patient was conscious, alert, and oriented to person, time, place, and event (COAx4). Respirations were at a rate of 16 breaths per minute and skin was normal for ethnicity. Pupils were equal and reactive to light. Medic advised the patient to stay hydrated, eat well, and to have a person drive for him at his second dose appointment. Patient was able to stand, walk without assistance and with a steady gait when he departed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I got a Mighty sore arm about 4 hours after injection. 30 hours later I began to feel agitated and grouchy. I woke up about 44 hours after vaccine with a painful and swollen left thumb joint.  I felt strangely tired. Immediately my left arm began a deep painful tingling from my shoulder to my fingertips, then began to feel numb and tingling and as if it were swelling. I lost my vision, felt like I was going to pass out, turned extremely pale, broke out in a cold sweat, then my shins and feet began to tingle. I felt as though I couldn?t breathe.  My vision came back but my body felt dislocated and my head a cinder block. It took great concentration to move my limbs and speak.  I couldn?t find the words I wanted.  This lasted for about 15 minutes just like a complete shock to my nervous system.  I was very irritable and exhausted for 4 days following.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Urge to have bowel movement. Abdominal cramping. Numbness and tingling of hands. Feeling of cold hands.   Patient was observed in the observation area post receiving COVID-19 Moderna Vaccine (dose 1). After about 5 minutes, patient was noted to have headache and other reactions.  She first developed developed  episode of bowel movement (urgent) with brief abdominal cramping sensation and shortly afterwards had numbness and tingling of fingers, and persistent feeling of cold hands though not cold to touch.  Denies chest pain, SOB, abdominal pain, cough, fevers, chills, palpitations, headache, nausea or vomiting.  No other complaints.   Patient was given a bottle of water to drink. She was taken to the observation room. Was instructed to perform ROM exercises of the shoulders and wrists. The movement of the upper extremities did not bring any relief. She was instructed to put her jacket on and to place her hands between her thighs to ameliorate the sensation of cold hands. Given her symptoms were not improving with these conservative measures and observation, she was encouraged to take a dose of Benadryl tablets which she brought with her. She took 50 mg Benadryl with water. The symptoms were not improving, but also not worsening. Her hands felt less cold when they were under the thighs but felt cold again shortly after withdrawing them. Patient practiced deep breathing exercises.  She was observed from about 12:55pm until  1:33pm. Patient carries prednisone around for instances of "allergic reactions" though she really hasn't had typical allergic IgE type reactions to the medications listed in her allergy list. Historically prednisone has brought some relief. She has never had a reaction to an injected vaccine in the past.  Patient was encouraged to take prednisone in the next 1-2 hours if still not feeling better given it has helped her in the past, but patient was informed it could impact the efficacy of the vaccination. She was instructed to discuss with allergist prior to getting 2nd Moderna Vaccination dose about whether a repeat dose would be needed or if pre-treatment of any sort should happen prior to 2nd dose.
OTHER_MEDS: inhaled budesonide PRN albuterol Cetirizine daily vitamin D3 topical clobetasol Cyclobenzaprine PRN Desonide ointment BID Fluocinolone ointment PRN Meloxicam daily Omeprazole daily Prednisone 20 mg as needed Simvastatin 20 mg QHS Valsartan

Finally one hour after shot, I purchased and took a dose of Benadryl which helped; at 530 PM took another dose of Benadryl as throat became increasingly scratchy /uncomfortable which again helped. Woke at 230 am finally feeling that reaction had passed. Pharmacist encouraged returning for next shot despite reaction. I participated in V-safe and reported reaction same day as vaccine. Researched on own to try and figure out 2nd dose or no as did not feel pharmacy was equipped for anaphylaxis. Finally called and spoke with Moderna on 4/5/21 and they indicated this was definitely an acute allergic reaction and should be reported to VAERS and 2nd dose was contraindicated     Spoke with pharmacist on 4/6 (date scheduled for 2nd dose - my husband was getting his 2nd dose) and she did not discourage 2nd dose but I elected to follow up with my allergy testing as recommended by CDC which is now pending

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient who is an associate at our store received her vaccine around 2:45pm.  She had no issues during the 15 minutes after her vaccine.  She went back to work but then came up the pharmacy around 6:45pm stating she was feeling short of breath.  After having her sit down to assess the situation the shortness of breath progressed rapidly to the point she wanted 911 called.  She stated it didn't feel like an asthma attack.  She also complained of feeling lightheaded.  The ambulance arrived and took her vitals.  They stated she was getting good oxygen but patient wanted transported to the hospital due to still being short of breath.  After arriving at the hospital she started having back pain as well.  The hospital ran several tests (the patient didn't know exactly which ones) and all but one came back fine. SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient received the vaccine on April 7, 2021.  Almost immediately after the vaccine, the patient developed some nonspecific complaints of headache, myalgias, arthralgias, fever and chills.  The symptoms lasted for several days and then seemed to resolve. She was then at her baseline until approximately April 15, 2021 when she noted that she was becoming bruised.  She had multiple ecchymoses on her lower extremities and this has never happened to her before.  She apparently began taking aspirin at that time.  According to the patient, she took 325 mg of aspirin on April 15th, 16th, and 17th.  She did not take any aspirin on April 18th but then on April 19th, she took 650 mg of aspirin.  On April 19, she had a telehealth visit.  They recommended that she go to an urgent care.  She went to an urgent care on the afternoon of April 19.  They told her that they were ill equipped to take care of her and then sent her to the emergency department. On arrival in the ED on 04/20/21 she was afebrile.  O2 saturation was 99% on room air.  Her other vital signs were unremarkable.  Her initial laboratory studies were notable for white count of 6.6 with a hemoglobin 15.2.  Her initial platelet count was 5,000.  Initial chemistry panel was completely unremarkable.  She was not having any headache, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, blurred vision or any neurologic symptoms.  She thinks that her lower extremities are swollen.  She was not having any myalgias or arthralgias.  Not having any abdominal pain, nausea vomiting, diarrhea, dysuria, urgency, frequency.  . The patient has no other specific complaints.The patient was admitted on 04/20/21.

There was a medical team on site and they intervened from the beginning. checking her pulse, blood pressure and lungs. They were very helpful and after 30-45 minutes she was back to normal. We didn't go to hospital. After three weeks, we went for the second shot and informed medical staff what happened during the first shot of the vaccine. They said this level of reaction is OK. If I had reviewed this page in detail, I would advise her not to take the shot. Anyways, she received one Benadryl 25 mg before the second shot. This time the reaction was more severe but medical team on site supported us and she received 3 more Benadryl pills. Everything went back to normal.  Our problem started after 2 weeks. SYMPTOM_TEXT: This RPH was called to assist patient at 11:27a. Patient stated he felt dizzy and I assisted patient to the floor. Once laying on floor I elevated patient's feet above his head. By stander reported that patient appeared to have blacked out right before I arrived on scene. Patient stayed upright in chair during blackout which only lasted a few seconds.  Patient stated he did eat breakfast but had not slept due to working overnight. Patient was assisted to sitting position on floor at 11:33a at which time he drank a bottle of water. After finishing bottle of water he stated he felt dizzy again and I assisted him back to a laying position on floor.  After 10 minutes I assisted patient back to a sitting position. After sitting for a few seconds patient stated he felt like he would get sick. Before I could return, patient vomitted on himself and over the floor. Patient continued to vomit/dry heave into trashcan for a few minutes. After patient was done getting sick, he drank another bottle of water. He sat for a few minutes prior to standing. At this time patient's mother-in-law had arrived at store to take patient home. Patient wanted to leave store immediately as he felt it was making him more uncomfortable due to current condition. Patient left store approximately 12p.

Pt asissted to floor, legs elevated up on a chair. Pt is alert .He stated, his name is (unlisted). Skin: pale, hands diaphoretic. Immediately, pt 's chest was pounding;HR was elevated , pt's eyes closed and he appeared attempt to answer this RN's questions as to how he feels, however, could not. Would not/could not open eyes. It appeared that he was shaking/mild jerking  as with the chills, however, this RN was discerning if it was seizure like activity. Upper body flushed/red. This lasted about 30-45 seconds.  Then pt.'s shakiness slowed down, heart pounding resolved and he opened his eyes. Able to squeeze nurse hand.   1:53 pm DPN   Came to assist.Ice pack to forehead  Pt was still shaky, but now responding.  Still w/ complaints of nausea, lightheadedness.   2:05 still lying on floor with legs elevated. 2:10 Sat up for 5 minutes. C/o nausea. Placed in wheelchair. Within 1 minute, pt. Is pale, shakiness returns, and c/o nausea. Returned to the floor , legs elevated and 9-1-1 initiated. HR steady, respirations -steady. MOC now present.Pt. now responding to MOC or RN's commands to squeeze hand or  Speak. Eyes closed. HR and RR steady.   9-11 arrived at 2: 15 pm and pt. Left facility with paramedics and MOC.

Within 6 hours after the vaccination, I experienced significant chills, then high fever, then body aches, then intense nausea. These symptoms were as expected and seemed to subside within 48 hours. However, the nausea did not subside and for the following 2 weeks, I experienced significant 'waves' of nausea brought on by various factors such as car/plane (motion sickness), sun exposure (75 degrees on a beach for 20 minutes), various foods, etc.   Approximately one week after the vaccination, I had several glasses of red wine (4 glasses within an 8 hour time period). I am not a big drinker, so this amount caused me to feel intoxicated but not enough to be completely inebriated. I slept for 6 hours and woke up feeling 'drunk'- extremely dizzy and nauseous. I proceeded to vomit non-stop (approximately 7 times) over the following 6 hours and could not get the nausea under control. In fact, I had to have a physician prescribe Zofran to stop the dizziness and nausea or else I was going to need fluids administered. This is extremely unusual for me. It felt like the nausea I had been feeling from the vaccine had somehow been intensified 10-fold because of the wine. The Zofran helped immensely however, the nausea (slight at this point- back down to what it was prior to the alcohol episode) continued to persist for another two weeks and a half weeks. A few days ago, it felt like I 'turned the corner'.  I am now three weeks out from the vaccination and the nausea is almost gone (90% gone).
LAB_DATA: At a routine (gyn) doctors visit, I mentioned the nausea and she suggested testing platelet levels. The test was yesterday (4/20/21) and the results

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I went to the vaccination site to get the second dose of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine.  During the vaccine injection by the technician, the needle and the syringe disconnected and the vaccine went over the car and my arm.  We were unable to determine how much of the dose may have been administered into my arm.  The needle definitely went into the injection site, but I don't know how much of the dose I had gotten.  I talked with the technician and supervisor on-site and they did not know what to do.  Their best recommendation was to get tested by my PCP for the anti-bodies in a couple of weeks.  I was not comforted by what I felt was ad-hoc answers to my questions, so I did not get an additional dose.  When I returned home, I called the CDC and looked online for what to do.  The official guidance is that an additional does of the vaccine should have been administered into my other arm.  I was not given an additional dose, so I do not know what I'm supposed to do.  I waited a couple of hours to see if I had the sore arm like the first dose, but I have not (as of yet) felt any affects from the vaccine injection.

After both the first and second vaccine shots, I had the same reaction.  15 to 20 minutes after the shot, I felt a numbness in my mouth.  I also had a slight throat constriction sensation that I know well given my history with severe allergic reactions to tree nuts.  However, to be clear, the reaction to the vaccine shots was far more mild than my reaction to tree nuts.  If I eat any tree nuts, I have a severe reaction that involves throat closure, hives, vomiting and related symptoms for 6-8 hours.  While the Epipen shot helps with keeping my throat open, it does not reduce all of the other symptoms.  Here, the throat constriction was only approx. 1/100th of the reaction I have when I eat tree nuts.  Further, the slight throat constriction and mouth numbness only lasted 10-15 minutes, as compared to 6-8 hours if I eat tree nuts. I did not need to use an Epipen.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 4/18/21 the day after receiving my second Pfizer vaccine. I awoke fatigued and with a sore right arm and fever of about 99. The fatigue increased, and then included extreme thirst despite drinking plain water throughout the morning and early afternoon, then I experienced slight nausea, then syncope after attempting to sit for a few moments, after having been resting (in a prone position) around 1 pm.  My husband was unable to revive me - he says my eyes were open but I was not responsive so he called 911. I regained consciousness after receiving saline via IV and then was taken to the ER for follow up testing, then released a few hours later - around 4 pm.  It it likely relevant to know I had passed out from fever brought on by flu during the very harsh flu season a few years before, at the onset of influenza, although vaccinated that year for flu.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The vaccination uncovered an ongoing, hitherto silent infection: after a few days, my teeth started hurting, with the pain intensity increasing over two days to the point where I had to see a dentist. It turned out I had a molar that was infected and needed a root canal. The immune response from the vaccine probably caused my body to react to the tooth infection as well. I normally wouldn't put the two things together, but I had a very similar reaction a few days after my flu vaccine back in October: sensitive teeth, wandering pain in different parts of my head, neck, and shoulder area. At that time, the dentist didn't find anything (although we now know it was probably the start of that same tooth becoming infected and dying), and antibiotics took care of it.    The root canal specialist I saw, the dr, said she is seeing a number of similar cases in her patients, where vaccinations bring out undetected problems. I actually consider that a good thing - I wouldn't want to have a rotting tooth that goes unnoticed for a while.
CUR_ILL: none known at the time, but see vaccination effect
PRIOR_VAX: Seasonal flu vaccine, in October 2020

I reviewed patient questionnaire form- she is a regular patient - I am very familiar with her rx and medical profiles. Lahough she answered yes to the medical condition and allergy questions - I determined she was ok to get the shot bc she said the dr wanted her to get the Covid vaccination mid April to early May.  I took pat's temp it was 97.9 F.  when i asked all of the prescreening covid/immunization questions and asked her if she was feeling well she said yes and she also passed all of the covid screening questions.  I proceeded to give her the vaccine. 4:20pm administered Moderna Covid 19 vaccination, 4:25pm I checked on patient - patient looked lethargic and when asked how she felt - she was severely slurring her words I could hardly understand her- she said she felt dizzy, not good, nauseous, about to faint. I told her to remain seated and brought her water and asked her to check her blood glucose on her Freestyle Libre sensor arm unit - it read 60. I asked her if she wanted orange juice, she said yes and a hot dog- we immediately brought her both- she checked her BG again at 4:30 and it went down to 58... I asked her if she had taken any meds before the shot - she said she took 2 glucose, 1 morhphine sulfate 15mg tablet and 1 gabapentin 300mg capsule right before she walked into the pharmacy.  At 4:45 she felt nauseous and dizzy. She took another glucose tablet from her bag and she also asked me to inject her glucagon shot- I gave her glucagon shot in her thigh at 4:50. I told her to stay seated - me and my tech were closely watching her the entire time. at 5pm she said she had to vomit so we watched her get up and near the bathroom while she vomited.  she sat back down and took her BG level again it was going up at 115. We continued to monitor her thru 6:10pm when she said she was a lot better and since she wanted to leave - I made sure she answered my questions clearly and she did not slur. She left the pharmacy at 6:15

DIAGNOSTIC STUDIES: 1. Chest x-ray that was normal. 2. CT angiography of the chest showing no abnormalities. 3. Echocardiogram showing no significant abnormalities.  HOSPITAL COURSE: A 24-year-old male, primary care patient, received a second dose of the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccination 3 days prior to admission.  Following this, he had a fever, chills, body aches, and then developed severe chest pain.  The pain was worse lying flat, better when sitting up and leaning forward and worse with a deep breath.  He had gone to an urgent Care and was recommended going to the emergency room.  The patient's troponins were elevated and his EKG was fairly classic for pericarditis.  He was felt to have probably viral myopericarditis and was admitted for observation.  He was placed on aspirin and colchicine.  He seems stable from Cardiology to be discharged on this regimen as well as symptomatic treatment.  It was not known whether the COVID vaccine was implicated with this or not.  DISCHARGE DISPOSITION: CONDITION:  Stable and improved.  MEDICATIONS: 1. Colchicine 0.6 mg b.i.d. 2. Aspirin 650 mg t.i.d. 3. Oxycodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg every 4 hours p.r.n. for pain. 4. Zofran 4 mg sublingual q.8 hours p.r.n. for nausea.  DIET: Regular.  ACTIVITY: As tolerated.  FOLLOWUP: With Cardiology on May 3rd.  If worsened pain, shortness of breath, or high fever, return for evaluation sooner.  In which case, steroids may be administered.

Acute idiopathic pancreatitis. Symptoms included tenderness and tightness in the center-left portion of the upper abdominal region. After 24 hours of discomfort, patient went to ED at. CT, ultrasound, and blood panel were conducted at that time. Ultrasound was negative for gallstones, blood panel showed highly elevated lipase (~600), slightly elevated WBC. Recommended admittance and abstinence from food for 36 hours. Treated with IV hydration, and IV antibiotics for potential diverticulitis. After 36 hours, put onto a liquid diet for 24 hours, then was allowed to eat a normal meal and was discharged without restrictions or modifications to diet or lifestyle.
LAB_DATA: All tests on 4/16/21. Ultrasound and CT found no irregularities, no gallstones. Initial blood panel showed highly elevated lipase (~600), and a slightly elevated WBC. By 4/18/21, lipase had returned to normal levels.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 10:00PM Saturday, 4/17/21 Sudden chest pain. Tried to sleep it off, pain lingered all day Sunday 4/18/21. 8:00PM went to local ER with same chest pain, had not gotten better. ER took blood draw, my troponin was 4.6 and doctors thought it was an error since I am 38 years old and otherwise health with no history of chest pain or family history of heat trouble. Second blood draw showed troponin at 5.0 getting worse. They called an ambulance and took me to the hospital nearby. Third blood draw showed 6.0 and I spiked at 10.0 overnight. I had several EKGs, a CT scan, and an angiogram. None of these showed any obstructions or blockages in the heart or blood vessels that could have caused the heart trauma. I had an echocardiogram which showed that my heart is only pumping at 50% which is low for a healthy young person who is a runner. I was diagnosed with myocarditis and with having had a Non-ST Segment Elevation Heart Attack. Again, I have no family history of this, I am otherwise healthy, I do not use drugs and I did not have any trauma to my chest, such as a car accident, that could have caused this. The only explanation is that it was related to the COVID shot, which I had roughly 48 hours before my sudden chest pain

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Two weeks post vaccination, I went from being completely healthy to losing feeling in my right foot. The neuropathy spread to both of my hands, my left shin, and my right arm and was also accompanied by joint pain. Neurological symptoms then set it including memory issues, word recall problems, migraines, visions issues, and severe brain fog. Reading, writing, and driving became extremely difficult. Cognitive function went from a 10 to a 3.  I never reported the issues to my gynecologist. Given my history of lyme disease and the similarities in symptoms, I suspected the vaccine had triggered a relapse instead sought treatment from my other physician. I'm reporting four years later because I only just found out about this! I had previously been fully vaccinated and never had a reaction.  Feeling in my extremities was slowly recovered over the course of treatment with my doctor over a year and a half. Neuropthy still happens in my hands at times. Cognitive function has returned to a 9, though some issues still present when I'm fatigued.  I was

SIRVA?  About 4 hours after receiving the vaccine, I experienced strong pain at the injection site that radiated down to my wrist. Two or three days after receiving the vaccine, I developed a burning pain deep in my shoulder area that was noticeable only when I swung my arm backwards, such as when walking.  The pain felt like it was deep in my shoulder joint.  I have attempted to locate the source of the pain by pressing my fingers deeply up into my armpit; however, I feel no pain when pressing into my armpit in this manner.    The pain level varies but has not subsided and continues to be noticeable when swinging my arms while walking. I didn?t strain, stretch, or otherwise stress my shoulder in any way that would cause this pain.    The pain has now become noticeable in the front of my shoulder, as well.   When I palpate the front of my shoulder, I feel distinct tenderness and pain.   My husband, who is an orthopedic surgeon, palpated the area and noted that the major pain seems to be coming from my biceps tendon.    I continue to feel pain in the biceps tendon area when I press on that area, as well as the pain deep within the shoulder that I cannot locate via palpation.  My main concern is whether I need to take my first dose of the Moderna vaccine again in the event I have SIRVA.

Patient came in for her first Moderna covid vaccine. After her vaccination, she went to sit outside the pharmacy to be monitored for 15 minutes as told. About 2 minutes after sitting down, her husband came to get my attention and stated the patient feels dizzy. When I came to assist, she stated she could no longer see but could still hear sounds. Her eyes started to roll to the back of her head and she fainted on her chair for about 5 seconds and recovered soon after. Then she said she could see again but was still feeling dizzy. She took a sip of water and continued to take deep breaths. Because she still felt dizzy and stated her vision was still blurry, her husband and I assisted her to the ground and had her lie on her back with her legs elevated. She instantly felt better and was able to see again but asked to take some glucose tablets, a few minutes later, because she felt her blood sugar might be low. She proceeded to take 2 of them. After a total of 30 minutes since the vaccine, she stated she felt well enough to go home. She then got up and left the facility with her husband.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1st shot: morning after EXTREME joint pain in shoulder of injection arm and other joint pain. Shoulder lasted 2 weeks, rest of body one week.   Headache day 3 for one day. Largest size about the top of a pint glass and got hard. Began to subside day 9? Felt generally cruddy for a week. No loss of taste or smell (in a super smeller) 2nd shot 5 weeks out: felt nauseous for about 15 minutes shortly after shot but it went away quickly.  Later on day of shot got THE LOUDEST PIERCING tinnitus I've ever had and STILL have it.  I've always had it but low grade, only noticeable when total silence or sick.  Now it's ALWAYS noticeable.  Flu like symptoms for 3 days.  Joint pain came back and hasn't really gone away for weeks now- it's been a month.    I was out of country and also went on a cave tour  and got really sick.  That's why I took the cipro when I returned and then had a reaction.  Was sick for over a year but now have "flares" of joint pain. I've tried telling several doctors but they don't seem ty think anything of it.  I dropped 40 lbs, was exhausted, had all kinds of problems and they never could figure out what was wrong me.  Now I have some random immune system issue?  I'm a high school teacher and I'm sick all the time.  I had a bunch of students who got a "virus" starting in October or November 2019-- they kept getting sick and then better and sick again but came to school. Then I got sick but not bad but had a tight chest, mild dry cough, and my tongue-- for several days it felt weird unlike anything before.  Didn't feel sick enough to see the doctor.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received her COVID-19 Vaccine. Before receiving her vaccine I asked all proper questions regarding history of reactions or if she felt ill at the moment (proper screening questions). The only thing the patient mentioned was that she had asthma and had been feeling it acting up recently but no current issues at the moment. I assured her that it was still ok to receive vaccine according to CDC guidelines. After the vaccine, the patient started getting an immediate headache. Soon after that she felt a wave of nausea. Right after that patient began stating that she felt her asthma attack coming on. I triaged the patient accordingly and checked her breathing/circulation/etc. I also asked her if she felt like she couldn't breathe or if she felt her throat closing up. She could still talk and said she did not feel her throat closing up. She just kept saying it was her asthma attack coming on (the same feeling she gets with her asthma acts up). I grabbed epi-pen in hand and came to her side assessing the reaction. She then began to have a light wheeze/hyperventilation and stated her asthma was the culprit. I immediately ran to pharmacy and grabbed albuterol inhaler which she also stated she uses. She used the inhaler did 2 puffs immediately. I stood by her side and kept assessing the reaction. She still had a light wheeze and was very anxious/emotional. I kept asking if she felt her throat closing up and kept asking her questions to make sure she could still talk. She said she just felt very dehydrated and severe asthma symptoms. Stood by her side for a few more minutes kept assessing with Epi-pen in hand ready to inject. I told her to do one more additional puff and after a few more minutes she could breathe more easily and felt a huge relief. Received emergency rx from her physician in order to fill prescription for her albuterol.
OTHER_MEDS: Multi vitamin, vitamin B12, flaxseed oil

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient while sitting in the post-vaccination area for 15 minutes, started experiencing lightheaded and faint when he got up. I instructed the patient to sit back down and he complied. I went to grab the patient water and calm him because he seemed a little anxious and then he started shaking, so we immediately called 911. I tapped him to see if he was okay, and he said yes was okay but really faint and the patient was sweating. I asked if he was having trouble breathing, but he denied. He drank the water and had chocolate and I kept conversing with him to assess for any physical/mental status changes, and during the conversation the patient said he usually feels faint and anxious when he gets blood drawn but did not mention it during the screening because he never has when receiving vaccinations. The patient was appearing to improve, less anxiousness, less sweating, and getting more color back to his face. When the EMS arrived within 5-10 mins, they assessed his vitals which were all normal and the patient requested not to be taken to the hospital. The EMT personnel felt the patient was doing okay and left. I had the patient stay for another 30 minutes to make sure he was remaining okay before he left.
ALLERGIES: None that the patient is aware of.
