SYMPTOM_TEXT: Janssen/J&J COVID-19 Vaccine EUA  Miller-Fischer Variant GBS - See continuation page #1 facial diplegia and ataxia  45-year-old male with history of schizophrenia presented with 6-day history of facial diplegia initially evaluated at outside facilities and transferred over here for further management.  There is a concern for Miller Fischer variant GBS.  No history of tick bite no signs of systemic infections.  Patient had a recent COVID-19 vaccine March 6th. On exam patient has pretty severe bilateral facial weakness in the lower motor apparent without any other cranial nerve involvement.  There is numbness in the lateral toes of the right foot and sensory ataxia on exam.  Patellar reflex and Achilles tendons were absent.  Remaining reflexes were present. Multiple labs are pending lumbar puncture is pending.  MRI brain is negative for enhancing lesions of the cranial and intra-articular portions of the facial nerve. After lumbar puncture will probably start the patient on IVIG if there was no signs of infection planning for 5-day course.  Recommend artificial tears and supportive management to prevent corneal ulcers from facial weakness.  OT and speech to see the patient. Assessment:  1.  Acute facial diplegia with bilateral peripheral cranial nerve VII dysfunction concerning for AIDP.  Symptoms started about 1 week ago.  House Brackmann scale 5 bilaterally.  Patient with metallic taste of tongue, pressure in his ears with some pain behind the ears.  Unable to close his eyes, raise his forehead, puff out his cheeks, or purse his lips.  No vibration sense to his chin.  Also noticing new numbness of his right toes and has absent R patellar reflex.  No recent noted infections although possible left mandibular tooth abscess noted on CT imaging and he reports a chronic "rotten tooth".  Patient had a COVID-19 Johnson & Johnson vaccine on March 4.  MRI brain with and without contrast is negative without noted enhancement of the facial nerve root.  Planning lumbar puncture today and then will discuss further treatment.  Will add moisture for his eyes and gabapentin for pain. 2.  Neutrophilic leukocytosis.  Unclear etiology.  May need to have the dentist look at his tooth and consider removal.  Will discuss further. 3.  History of schizophrenia.  Patient denies any acute complaints with this but is anxious to restart his lithium which is okay from our standpoint. 4.  Tobacco use 5.  Hypothyroidism.  Continue home levothyroxine. Plan: - LP, see orders - motor sensory neuropathy panel, b12, ANA, ACE, EBV Ab panel, RPR, Lyme reflexive panel, HIV, TSH, UA -Eyedrops and ointment to bilateral eyes -Gabapentin 100 mg 3 times daily -SLP to see History of Present Illness: 45-year-old male with a history of schizophrenia and tobacco use who presents with facial diplegia for the last 6 to 7 days.  On Saturday night a week ago he had a fullness in his bilateral ears and thought he may have an ear infection.  He woke up Sunday morning (March 21) with bifacial weakness and dysarthria.  He has a metallic taste in his tongue.  He feels somewhat swollen and sore in the posterior area.  He still has a full feeling in his ears but no hearing loss.  He cannot completely close his eyes.  He has no movement of his forehead he cannot puff out his cheeks.  He has had difficulty getting food to back of his mouth to swallow.  His eyes are watering.  He has some occasional stabbing, ice pick pains behind his ears, mild at present.  He feels numb in his perioral area.  Since occurrence this is not worsened or improved.  He denies any illnesses in the last month or 2.  He has had some diaphoresis at home since this occurred.  No palpitations.  No bowel or bladder issues.  No difficulty walking.  Denies shortness of breath.  After transfer here and when he is asked he has noted some numbness in his third through fifth toes on the right foot which is new.  He had a Johnson & Johnson COVID-19 vaccination on March 4.  He has been on lithium since he was a child and recently was placed on Zoloft.  He denies any new mental health issues but stopped his medications when the symptoms occurred as he was concerned there might be a potential side effect.  At the outside hospital he had a CT of the neck which did note lucency around the root of his remaining left mandibular molar suspicious for abscess as well as large dental caries.  He reports knowing he has had a rotten tooth on the back left for a long time.  He is missing most of his upper teeth except a couple molars ("from bad decisions in his young years").  He had gone into the local ED about 3 days ago and they gave him a prescription for amoxicillin, prednisone, Zyrtec and Benadryl.  He had a couple doses of amoxicillin and prednisone before he went back to the ED yesterday with ongoing symptoms. Medical History Past Medical History: Diagnosis Date o Anxiety   o Paranoid schizophrenia  o Smoking status: Current Every Day Smoker     Packs/day: 0.50     Years: 30.00     Pack years: 15.00 Substance and Sexual Activity o Alcohol use: Yes     Frequency: 2-4 times a month o Drug use: Not Currently o Sexual activity: Defer Patient is allergic to geodon [ziprasidone hcl]; haldol [haloperidol]; abilify [aripiprazole]; and latuda [lurasidone]. Review of Systems he has a history of low back pain with right leg radiculopathy for which she had a radiofrequency ablation done in the past. Physical Exam: Current Vital Signs: BP 139/77 (BP Location: Left arm, Patient Position: Lying)  | Pulse 89  | Temp 36.6 �C (97.9 �F) (Oral)  | Resp 18  | Ht 1.702 m (5' 7")  | Wt 110 kg (241 lb 6.5 oz)  | SpO2 97%  | BMI 37.81 kg/m�  Labs: Sodium 137 Potassium 4.4 BUN 16 Creatinine 1.05 Glucose 109 Lithium level 0.2 WBC 16.64 Hemoglobin 14.5  DISCHARGE SUMMARY Hospital Course: 45-year-old male with a history of schizophrenia who had 6 to 7 days now of complaints of upper forehead/facial weakness, eyes watering leading to blurry vision until he wipes away the excess and numbness of his lips and mouth and tongue feeling thick.  He noticed that his speech was a little different and he felt muffled and cottonmouth.  He had a little bit of issue eating as he states that he had to put his food in the back of his throat so that his tongue would not push the food out of his mouth.  He denies any numbness around his maxilla or mandible or cheeks.  He stopped all of his medications abruptly when he had the symptoms as he thought it may be a side effect from something.  He denies any recent environmental or insect exposure.  No fevers or chills.  No URI symptoms.  No ear pain.  No nausea or vomiting. Patient was ultimately diagnosed with Miller Fisher variant GBS secondary to Johnson & Johnson COVID-19 vaccine.  Neurology evaluated and started IVIG treatment for 5 total doses.  He progressively improved with his symptoms throughout the 5 days of hospitalization.  He completed IVIG therapy on 4/1/2021. I personally evaluated the patient on the day of discharge he was doing well and had no complaints.  He is to follow-up with neurology in 1 to 2 months.  FMLA paperwork was filled out.  He was discharged with eye ointment solution and told to protect his eyes.  It was neurology recommendation that he take at least 2 months off of work in order to do so.  I had no changes in my physical exam�significant cranial nerve deficits associated with primary diagnosis.  Otherwise no focal neurologic deficits observed in the upper and lower extremities.  Heart was regular rate and rhythm lungs are clear.  Abdomen had normal bowel sounds and was nontender.  He has no peripheral edema to speak of. Miller-Fischer Variant GBS - F/u with neuro in 1-2months

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Fever, tired, arm pain, chill. All these symptoms started from the second day i took the vaccine, and lasted for one day long.

Starting two weeks after the injection I became very exhausted and sleepy.  I went from having insomnia type sleep to sleeping about 14-20 hours a day.  I had two negative Covid  nasal swab tests in the following  week as well as a negative Covid blood test.  During this time my heart rate was increasing, and my oxygen levels were lower than normal.  Drs have done  full lab work ups multiple times over the last 2 months,  chest X-ray, 24 hr heart monitor, and EKG as well as several virtual dr appts and an in person  endocrinologist appointment this week.  The results of my 24 he heart rate monitor showed that my minimum heart rate was 86 over a full 24 hour period including sleep.  My normal sleep HR is 58-62.  My endocrinologist attributes the extreme tiredness and increased heart rate to the vaccine.  She also noticed in blood work that it has possibly affected my thyroid and I will be put on medication for that.  These symptoms have continued for over 2 months now and have affected my ability to work and conduct normal routines in my life.  One example is that my mother had to help me dry my hair because I was so tired and weak.  I have been unable to stay awake long enough to do much other than attend the work hours needed in a day and a occasionally a few additional light activities from the couch like using my phone or watching TV.  The symptoms ramped back up after my second vaccination.  I have been able to stay awake more hours on and off over the past week, but I am still far from back to normal.
LAB_DATA: 2/26 negative Covid nasal swab 3/1 negative Covid blood test 3/1 other lab work  3/6 24 heart monitor lowest heart rate 86 bpm 3/8- chest X-ray negative 4/13- EKG normal 4/20 more lab work
OTHER_MEDS: Metformin ER 2000mg daily Ozempic 1mg weekly Adderall 30 mg daily
HISTORY: Diabetes Asthma  Obesity (197 lbs at time of vaccine)
PRIOR_VAX: See previous description

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 3- 5 minutes after felt strange mild sensation as if pins and needles was moving throughout my body from the injection site. I also started to breathe differently. Couldn't tell if my heart rate changed or not.   At about 5 minutes, I started to feel light-headed and nauseous as if I just had blood taken or an IV in my, likely a drop in blood pressure. I was reading a book, put it down on my lap as I couldn't focus on reading and considering to get help. At that moment, I passed out, hunched over in my chair staring at the floor.   This moment likely lasted for about 1 minute, but felt like 20. I was in a dream like state and at one point had a series of images and/or memories flash by in a sequence. Then, I felt like I was half asleep but couldn't tell what I was staring at but knew that I had to "wake up".   Then , I was surrounded by people who helped me up. At this moment I felt very weak and tired and was sweating profusely. My right hand felt very weak.   About 10 minutes later, I started feeling better. I was given water which seemed to help. I would have waves of mild nausea come and go that eventually subsided. I also felt random cramping around my stomach/lower chest area and lower right side rib cage area.   At about 15 -20 minutes felt confident to walk to the bathroom and throughout the store. Eventually, I felt confident to drive safely home.  At the time of writing this (approx 2 hours later), I'm feeling random sensations/feelings of itchyness throughout my body. No sign of hives.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was given her first dose of Moderna at a drive through clinic and instructed to wait the 15 minutes for observation.  During this time patient and her mother notified the staff member that patient was not feeling including feeling dizzy and nauseated and feeling abdominal discomfort with numbness and tingling of her tongue and lips.  RN  assessed patient and took vitals. Patient was alert and oriented and able to speak in full sentences,  denied SOB, chest pain and was breathing comfortably.  BP was 80/40 HR 50's, RR 18. The PA at the clinic where the clinic was being held assessed patient and assessed lung sounds which were clear and the patient then reported feeling "a lot better".  Color returned to her lips and face.  Patient was asked to stay on-site for continued observation before leaving. Approximately 10 minutes later patient asked to use the bathroom in our clinic.  She was advised she could go as long as her Mom was allowed to go in with her in case she experienced dizziness or needed help.   After 5-10 minutes the patient was still in the bathroom. RN who worked inside clinic checked on patient who reported diarrhea more dizziness and weakness.  After discussion with the provider it was  and patient's mother it was decided that the mother would drive the patient to the nearest emergency room although this patient is a (Name) patient, for further and continued assessment.  At this time the patient was speaking in full sentences able to walk and and did not report any breathing problems.  After helping patient back to her vehicle RN called ER to give report to the charge nurse.
LAB_DATA: See Hospital Emergency Room visit for this information.  This patient was not a patient of our clinic, she is a (Name) patient so we do not have access to this information.

At time of event, while seated, suddenly entire face went cold/numb, blood pressure seemed to drop significantly (did not have ability to monitor it), face and lips were pale, fingertips were cold. Felt like fainting, could not move or send a text message / call for help for about 10 minutes. I was afraid I was going to faint or fall off the seat but was able to prop myself against a box. The rest of my body was not cold and I had to remove a sweatshirt because it felt too warm. I have had a few vasovagal reactions in the past 20 years (very rare events, about 1x per year at most and usually much less frequent than that). I felt dehydrated despite drinking water throughout the day. After I was able to move again, I lay down for about 30 minutes with monitoring and gradually felt normal again. The injection site has felt very mildly sore but nothing unusual for a vaccination.
ALLERGIES: Sulfa drugs (adverse reaction in childhood once)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: ED NOTE is as follows...from 4/21/21 @ 21:47    a 28 y.o. male who to the emergency room with reports of a headache for the last 48 hours.  He reports this as being one of the worst headaches he has ever had.  He was seen at urgent care and given Toradol, Zofran and Benadryl and still rates his pain an 8 out of 10.  He does feel pressure behind his eyes.  And reports vomiting in the parking lot at urgent care.  He denies abdominal pain back pain, neck pain, shortness of breath, chest pain, numbness or tingling or any other worsening concerns.  Reports that he did receive a recent Johnson & Johnson vaccination.  Patient states he does vape.  He occasionally drinks alcohol he denies any illicit drugs.  Patient denies any head trauma.   Diagnosis management comments: This is a 28-year-old male arrives to the emergency room with reported migraine headache for the last 48 hours.  He did report that he was go to urgent care in which he received a migraine cocktail of Zofran, Benadryl and Toradol.  Patient reported that his headache was not resolved so urgent care sent him on for further evaluation.  Patient upon arrival had a negative neurological exam however he did report that he had pressure behind his eyes.  Was unable to see any papilledema on funduscopic exam.  Check patient's pressures bilaterally and they were 21 and 18.  Patient did report to me that this was the worst headache of his life.  I did administer IV fluids here as well as Tylenol and morphine.  Patient did report some improvement.  Patient did report in his past medical history had a recent Johnson & Johnson vaccination.  A CBC and CMP was obtained.  Did have thrombocytopenia with a count of 66.  Since my exam was PERRL with normal extraocular movements.  He had no eye redness or eye pain.  Of low concerns for any iritis or uveitis.  Patient's patient CT of his head did show a abnormal CT that had a dense appearing superior sagittal sinus that was representing a venous thrombosis.  Radiologist did recommend a MRI MRV.  An MRI and MRV was ordered.  Patient MRI MRv did show findings are consistent with a venous thrombosis involving the right jugular right transverse sinus and superior sagittal sinus there is also a patchy edematous change within the subcortical white matter areas bilaterally and symmetrically.  There was no CVA.  With patient's reported migraine headache.  Reported blurred vision, low platelets, recent vaccination I do believe patient has vaccine induced thrombotic thrombocytopenia.  With this finding I did converse with my overseeing physician Calls were made out to neurology and then a call out did prefer to have patient started on IVIG at 1 g/kg daily for 2 days and blood thinner Xarelto 15 mg p.o. twice daily.  These orders were initiated.  Internal med services was consulted and with conversations of family, internal med services out possible transfer that an interventionalists could be available if patient needed it.  Report was given at 2100 upon my end of shift.
LAB_DATA: 4/21/2021 @ 1659 Platelets 66 D-Dimer Qunantatative > 12,800 INR 1.2  CT  of head without contrast: 1. Fairly abnormal CT of the head with patchy areas of abnormal attenuation throughout the white matter, which may represent edema. 2. Dense-appearing superior sagittal sinus, potentially representing venous thrombosis. 3. Recommend a contrast-enhanced MRI of the brain, as well as an MRV of the brain. 4. The findings were called at 6:15 PM  MRI Brain with and without Contrast: 1. The findings are most consistent with venous thrombosis with involvement of the right jugular, right transverse sinus and superior sagittal sinus. 2. There is patchy edematous change within the subcortical white matter areas bilaterally and symmetrically. No CVA. 3. The findings are called at 8:15 PM.  MRI Angiogram Heat without Contrast: 1. The findings are most consistent with venous thrombosis with involvement of the right jugular, right transverse sinus and superior sagittal sinus. 2. There is patchy edematous change within the subcortical white matter areas bilaterally and symmetrically. No CVA. 3. The findings are called at 8:15 PM.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediately after injection (seconds after the band aid was placed on shot area), I started to see spots and felt faint, then I progressively felt like it was  getting harder and harder to breath, I felt like my throat was slowly closing in, the EMT gave me oxygen which helped, then I started to feel a numbing sensation start in my hands, work down my spine and then to my feet. My hands continued to get stiffer until they formed claw like shapes and completely stiffened, the EMT had a monitor on my finger to gauge my pulse and they said it was a shooting up and down. My body was sweating profusely. After 20 minutes I felt my hands loosen and my body started to return to normal. The ambulance checked me on site and offered me to go to hospital, but since I was feeling better by that point, so I declined. Once I was feeling better, they tried to take my sugar level, but could not draw any blood when pricking my finger (they assumed this was because all my blood rushed to my vital organs, so blood would be hard to draw/they said this was probably also why my limbs went numb). They told me that I  could possibly be allergic to the vaccine based on the reaction. I was driven home 30-40 minutes later, I felt a bit light headed in the car, but slept for the rest of the day. The following day I just felt very tired, which is probably to be expected after the first shot.
LAB_DATA: I have an upcoming appointment on Monday, 4/26  with an allergist  who has said they can test me for similar ingredients in the Moderna vaccine to see if I may have any related allergies.   I'd like to better understand if I should or should not be getting my second dose of Moderna, which is currently scheduled for May 1st.
ALLERGIES: No known allergies. Going to an allergist on 4/27 to test if allergic to ingredients in vaccine due to reaction immediately following first dose.

It has hurt enough that I am not able to apply deoderant or really use my arm for daily tasks. I am currently in Day 5 after my vaccine has stayed pretty consistent with Day 4. No new bumps, but similar pain and swelling. Pain seems to reduce minimally when taking ibuprofen. I also had a headache on Day 5.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This was an administration error, not an adverse event. The Health Department had left over vaccine at the end of clinic and opened this up to employees and their families. These appointments were not registered using as per our usual practice, but were done as walk-ins on paper. The vaccinating nurse was a fully vetted retired RN who had undergone training many times and had worked at many clinics. The vacinee's age was stated on the requisition form but the vaccinator missed this and gave Moderna to a 17-yr-old. Employees training always includes discussion of target group and age requirements. This occured at the end of a busy clinic on a day that included both electronically registered and non-registered individuals, which is not our usual practice. We will avoid this practice in the future and will continue to address age requirement in trainings, stressing the importance of checking this parameter in people who did not register electronically. If this person had tried to register electronically, she would not have been able to proceed after entering her age. Writer discussed with CDC and was told to administer dose 2 as planned and to complete VAERS reports for each dose.

Client received first dose of Moderna at 0848. Per vaccinator who gave injection - client was tearful and reported anxiety about receiving injection. Per client she reports that her arm immediately felt "heavy and tingly".  She did not tell anyone and proceded to post-vaccine monitoring area with her spouse. She reports that she started feeling "more tingly" at 0903. By 0908 she reported difficulty breathing and PHN responded.  She was making occasional gasping sounds and crying. She was able to speak and HR was  ~72 BPM per her wearable device. Respirations were shallow and frequent.  Spouse was supportive and stated that she was having a panic attack because she hadn't had a shot since her childhood and was very anxious about the vaccine. He also reported that they hadn't slept or eaten anything due to attending to elderly dog  and that "this is what her panic attacks look like". PHN attempted to have client take deeper, slower breaths while continuing to assess. Client's breathing improved. Meanwhile 3 other PHNs responded and then client began to have difficulty breathing again. One PHN called 911. She then reported she was feeling  "tingly everywhere"  and her "eyes felt like they were sweating" Then her hands began to cramp and her face was pale. 0.5 mL epinephrine injected in RA at 0910 by another PHN. Vitals taken at 0910 were 120/85, 73bmp. She reported that her symptoms were beginning to alleviate.  EMS arrived at 0915 followed by paramedics at 0918. Vitals at 0918 were 110/68, 60 bmp, 100% SpO2. Vitals at 0922 were 131/98 and 62 BPM.  Paramedics discussed possibility of it being a panic attack but recommended going to hospital to be monitored - discussed spouse driving vs paramedic transport. At this point client shared that her HR at approx 0905 was 45 bpm per her wearable device. EMS discussed how this is another indicator of anaphylaxis and recommended ambulance transport. Client agreed and she was transported at 0930.
LAB_DATA: unknown what happened after client left sight

While administering a 2nd dose of Moderna vaccine, there was a malfunction with the sharps device, which resulted in an indeterminate portion of the vaccine being administered to the patient (i.e. a portion of the dose sprayed out of the sharps device). We had a previous incident in which a nurse inadvertently administered an inaccurate amount of vaccine (less than the 0.5 ml) and we were advised by the immunization program, at that time, to re-administer the full dose to those individuals as soon as possible. Given that information and not knowing what amount of vaccine the patient received, we followed this same guidance. The patient agreed to receive a re-administration of the full dose of vaccine, so a full dose was administered immediately. Both doses were placed in the left deltoid. We monitored the patient for 20 minutes post-vaccination and no concerns were noted. PHN did place a follow up call to the patient on 4/22/21 but has not heard back from her.

He slept through the night (skipping his nightly feed--this has only ever happened three times since birth so very uncommon) and was still cranky and tired/sleepy the next day. His fever broke about 30hrs after onset. He has since had a significant change in wet/dirty diapers-- his total, daily wet diapers have decreased and his dirty diapers have gone from semi-solid stool to very wet, more explosive, and incredibly grainy/gritty ever since (it's been a week and a half now since my dose). I have continued to breastfeed during this whole time.

I would get a flutter of my heart racing then a rush of dizziness and felt like I was going out pass out. It was really strange. It is the next day and my  tongue still feels a little bit like pins and needles but overall feeling better this morning.
